abstract:
 Large volumes of videos are continuously recorded from cameras deployed for traffic control and surveillance with the goal of answering ``after the fact'' queries: {\em identify video frames with objects of certain classes (cars, bags)} from many days of recorded video. While advancements in convolutional neural networks ( 
ame have enabled answering such queries with high accuracy, they are too expensive and slow. We build , a system for low-latency and low-cost querying on large video datasets. {
ame} uses cheap ingestion techniques to index the videos by the objects occurring in them. At ingest-time, it uses compression and video-specific specialization of \cnns. {
ame handles} the lower accuracy of the cheap \cnns by judiciously leveraging expensive 
ame at query-time. To reduce query time latency, we cluster similar objects and hence avoid redundant processing. Using experiments on video streams from traffic, surveillance and news channels, we see that  uses $58	imes$ fewer GPU cycles than running expensive ingest processors and is $37	imes$ faster than processing all the video at query time.
